  "prompt": "What is the difference between UMTS and LTE?",
  "response": "Here are the key differences between UMTS (Universal Mobile Telecommunications System) and LTE (Long-Term Evolution):\n\nUMTS:\n1. 3G technology\n2. Uses WCDMA radio access technology\n3. Lower data speeds (up to 2 Mbps)\n4. Circuit-switched voice calls\n5. Deployed in early 2000s\n6. Narrower bandwidth\n7. Less spectral efficiency\n\nLTE:\n1. 4G technology\n2. Uses OFDMA and SC-FDMA radio access\n3. High data speeds (up to 100 Mbps)\n4. Packet-switched voice calls (VoLTE)\n5. Deployed around 2010\n6. Wider bandwidth\n7. Higher spectral efficiency\n8. All-IP network architecture\n9. Lower latency\n10. Better network performance and capacity\n\nThe main differences center around technology generation, data speeds, network architecture, and overall performance. LTE represents a significant technological advancement over UMTS, offering faster data transmission, improved network efficiency, and better user experience.",
